oach and Methodology -- tChapter 15. Developing a Business Case for Accessible Tourism -- tChapter 16. Stakeholder Analysis of Accessible Tourism -- tChapter 17. Web Design, Assistive Technologies and Accessible Tourism -- tChapter 18. Technology Platforms and Challenges -- tChapter 19. Conclusion: Universal Approaches to Accessible Tourism0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aInclusion, disability, an ageing population and tourism are increasingly important areas of study due to their implications for both tourism demand and supply. This book therefore sets out to explore and document the current theoretical approaches, foundations and issues in the study of accessible tourism. In drawing together the contributions to this volume the editors have applied broader social constructionist approaches to understanding the accessible tourism phenomena. Accessible tourism, as with any area of academic study is an evolving field of academic research and industry practice. As with other areas of tourism, the field is multidisciplinary, and is influenced by various disciplines including geography, disability studies, economics, public policy, psychology and marketing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPeople with disabilitiesxTravel. 0aTourism. 4aDisability: social aspects. 4aTourism industry. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Hospitality, Travel & Tourism.2bisacsh  aAccessibility research.  aAccessibility.  aAccessible tourism.  aAccessible travel.  aAgeing population.  aDisability legislation.  aDisability studies.  aDisability.  aInclusion.  aSocial constructionist approaches.1 aAmbrose, I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArola, E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary